actions.comment:
Thanks for the clear repro code — the shader-only performance difference is a useful signal.

As a workaround while we investigate, you can pre-render the gradient to an image once (when the size changes) and draw that cached image each frame instead of applying the shader directly:

```csharp
// Once, when size changes:
using var tempSurface = SKSurface.Create(new SKImageInfo((int)FireField.Width, (int)FireField.Height));
tempSurface.Canvas.DrawRect(0, 0, FireField.Width, FireField.Height, BG);
cachedGradient?.Dispose();
cachedGradient = tempSurface.Snapshot();

// In PaintSurface, replace the DrawRect+shader with:
canvas.DrawImage(cachedGradient, 0, 0);
```

This avoids re-evaluating the gradient shader per-pixel on every frame.

A couple of questions to help us narrow this down:
1. Are you using `SKCanvasView` (CPU rendering) or `SKGLView` (GPU-accelerated)? GPU rendering handles gradient shaders natively and may not show this regression.
2. How large is the `FireField` area (approximate pixel dimensions)?
3. How frequently is `PaintSurface` called — is this running as an animation loop?
